I see two problems with your code.
1. The `if` conditions in your code use [bitwise operators][1]. You need to change them to *logical* [operators][2].
2. After changing them to logical operators, you need to correctly group them.

Logical operators are binary operators, i.e. they have two operands. Hence, when you compile your code, the operands will be grouped. Take, for example, your first `if` statement:  
(Note that I have replaced the bitwise operators with logical operators.)
```java
if (num1 &lt;= 31 &amp;&amp; num2 == 1 || num2 == 5 || num2 == 3 || num2 == 7 || num2 == 8 || num2 == 10 || num2 == 12) {
```
Operators are evaluated according to their precedence and `&amp;&amp;` comes before `||` so the first part of the `if` condition to be evaluated will be:
```java
num1 &lt;= 31 &amp;&amp; num2 == 1
```
If the value of `num1` is 56, then the result of the above is *false*. That result will be used as the first operand in the next part of the evaluation which will be:
```java
false || num2 == 5
```
If the value of `num2` is 5, then the result of the above is *true*. And since the remainder of the condition contains only `||` operators, evaluation will stop and the whole `if` condition is considered *true* and that&#39;s why your code prints YES when you enter 56 for `num1` and 5 for `num2`.

What you want is to group all the `||` operators so that they will be considered as a single operand. Hence the `if` condition should be:
```java
if (num1 &lt;= 31 &amp;&amp; (num2 == 1 || num2 == 5 || num2 == 3 || num2 == 7 || num2 == 8 || num2 == 10 || num2 == 12)) {
```
The above `if` can be read as...
&gt; if `num1` is less than or equal to 31 **and** `num2` is one of 1 or 3 or 5 or 7 or 8 or 10 or 12

