Setting the [MDC][1] and then using that value in the [log pattern][2] is the way to go.

For a spring boot web app just add a filter after the [SecurityContextHolderFilter][3] with the security filter chain API.

A simple example for a filter configuration:

    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        return http.addFilterAfter((servletRequest, servletResponse, filterChain) -&gt; {
                    try {
                        // get the username from current user&#39;s authentication
                        Optional.ofNullable(SecurityContextHolder.getContext())
                                .map(SecurityContext::getAuthentication)
                                .ifPresent(authentication -&gt; MDC.put(&quot;user-name&quot;, authentication.getName()));
                        filterChain.doFilter(servletRequest, servletResponse);
                    } finally {
                        MDC.remove(&quot;user-name&quot;);
                    }
                }, SecurityContextHolderFilter.class)
                .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -&gt; ....)
                .build();
    }
        
Configure the slf4j(logback) pattern to use the mdc value in your `application.yaml`.

In the following pattern `%mdc{user-name:-NO_USER}` will use the user&#39;s user name set in the filter or `NO_USER` if the user-name variable is not set.

    logging.pattern.console: &quot;[%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS}] %-5level [%mdc{user-name:-NO_USER}] [%t{15}] [%logger{36}-:%line]: %m%n&quot;

